      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the perplexing world of student loans, where the principal balance seems to be playing hide and seek with your hard-earned money. It's like a sneaky goblin hoarding your gold coins, isn't it? Well, let's dive into the goblin's lair of interest calculations.\n\nWhen you make your monthly payment, a portion of it goes towards the principal balance, like a brave knight slaying goblins, while the rest goes towards the interest, like goblins sneaking away with your loot. The interest is calculated based on the remaining principal balance at the beginning of each month, multiplied by the monthly interest rate. This rate is determined by the annual percentage rate (APR) of your loan, divided by 12.\n\nSo, imagine your loan as a treasure chest filled with gold coins (the principal balance). Each month, the goblins (interest) take a small portion of the gold coins, based on how much gold is left in the chest. The more gold coins you have, the more goblins can take. As you make payments, you're slowly slaying goblins and reducing the amount of gold they can take, but it's a slow battle, and the goblins are quite cunning.\n\nRemember, the goblins (interest",
